SIMPLE: trochoid
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Trochoid
<hw>Tro"choid</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Gr. <?/ a wheel +
<ets>-oid</ets>; cf. F. <ets>trocho⟦ium⟧de</ets>. See
<er>Troche</er>.]</ety> <fld>(Geom.)</fld> <def>The curve described by
any point in a wheel rolling on a line; a cycloid; a roulette; in
general, the curve described by any point fixedly connected with a
moving curve while the moving curve rolls without slipping on a second
fixed curve, the curves all being in one plane. Cycloids, epicycloids,
hypocycloids, cardioids, etc., are all trochoids.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trochoid</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Trochoid
<hw>Tro"choid</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Anat.)</fld>
<def>Admitting of rotation on an axis; -- sometimes applied to a pivot
joint like that between the atlas and axis in the vertebral
column.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Top-shaped; having a flat base
and conical spire; -- said of certain shells.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>Of or pertaining to the genus
Trochus or family <fam>Trochidae</fam>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Trochoidal</ent>⟦br⟧
